%I A395489 #18 Apr 27 2026 05:20:17
%S A395489 1,2,4,7,13,22,38,67,121,208,346,663,1067,2084,3650,5621,10187,20228,
%T A395489 33960,67673,106919,167302,316644,632549,988585,1672754,3243116,
%U A395489 5502723,9032101,18060326,26876518,53747047,97409341,162001788,320354230,488138971,761529731
%N A395489 Number of gcd-closed subsets of {1,2,...,n}.
%C A395489 A set S is gcd-closed if i, j in S always implies that gcd(i,j) in S.  This concept was introduced by Beslin and Ligh (see Links), but it appears no one up to now studied the number of such sets.
%C A395489 From _David A. Corneth_, Apr 26 2026: (Start)
%C A395489 Some branch and cutting can be used to calculate terms for this sequence. Let's introduce some notation for presence of numbers in [1..n]. Let "X" denote the number at this position is not present. Let a number denote that that number is most definitely present. Let ? denote the number at this position may or may not be present.
%C A395489 So [X, 2, 3, ?, ?] denotes: in a set, 1 is most definitely not present, 2 and 3 are present and 4 and 5 may not be present.
%C A395489 From this information we can find that any such set is not gcd-closed. gcd(2, 3) = 1 and 1 is not present.
%C A395489 Up to 4 there is 1 position "?". This means that 2^1 = 2 subsets of {1..n} are not gcd-closed, which is found from [X, 2, 3]. These subsets are {2, 3} and {2, 3, 4}.
%C A395489 Similar, up to 5 there are two positions with ? which means 2^2 = 4 subset of [1..n] are not gcd-closed from [X, 2, 3]. These subsets are {2, 3}, {2, 3, 4}, {2, 3, 5}, {2, 3, 4, 5}.
%C A395489 After finding the number Q of subsets that are not gcd-closed we have a(n) = 2^n - Q. (End)
%D A395489 J. Shallit, The number of gcd-closed subsets of {1,2,...,n}, in preparation (2026).
%H A395489 S. Beslin and S. Ligh, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0004972700017457">Another generalisation of Smith's determinant</a>, Bull. Austral. Math. Soc. 40 (1989), 413-415.
%F A395489 Limit_{n->infinity} (log_2 a(n))/n exists and is approximately 0.82, but it seems difficult to estimate the limit precisely.
%e A395489 For n = 4 the three omitted subsets of {1,2,3,4} are {2,3}, {3,4}, and {2,3,4}, so a(4) = 2^4 - 3 = 13.
%o A395489 (Python)
%o A395489 from math import gcd
%o A395489 from itertools import count, islice
%o A395489 def agen(): # generator of terms
%o A395489     G = [0]
%o A395489     for n in count(1):
%o A395489         yield len(G)
%o A395489         newG, maskn = [], 1<<n
%o A395489         for g in G:
%o A395489             i, passes = n-1, True
%o A395489             while i:
%o A395489                 if (1<<i)&g:
%o A395489                     if not (1<<gcd(i, n))&g:
%o A395489                         passes = False
%o A395489                         break
%o A395489                 i -= 1
%o A395489             if passes:
%o A395489                 newG.append(maskn|g)
%o A395489         G += newG
%o A395489 print(list(islice(agen(), 25))) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Apr 25 2026
%K A395489 nonn,new
%O A395489 0,2
%A A395489 _Jeffrey Shallit_, Apr 25 2026
%E A395489 a(33)-a(36) from _Michael S. Branicky_, Apr 25 2026
